Rating: 4
Absolutely the best cranberry sauce. I use a "spiced cider" - which adds a nice flavor. I also use less liquid 1 1/4 cup and tie the cloves & cinnamon sticks into cheesecloth. This is a favorite and I have shared the recipe with family and friends.

Rating: 4
I've made this sauce for the past four Thanksgiving. This year I used 2 cups brown sugar instead of honey just for a little change, and it still tastes fantastic. I use a little less cider than called for, though, otherwise it has to cook for much longer than 15 minutes to thicken to the right consistency. Also I recommend putting the cloves in cheesecloth (or even a coffee filter, tied at the top), as the can be quite difficult to fish out and not pleasant to bite into if you miss one!

Rating: 4
A holiday tradition, this cranberry sauce. Although it does take longer than 15 minutes to reduce the apple cider--more like 25. Always good!

Rating: 4
This recipe really fits the bill for my perfect cranberry sauce. I've tried all sorts of different recipes over the years and this is the first one that appeals to both cranberry sauce lovers and those who usually pass it up. I added a pinch of fresh ground nutmeg and an extra cinnamon stick and cooked it a little longer than called for so that it wouldn't be runny. For me this recipe really allows cranberry sauce to shine and to fill its role as something you take a tiny bite of in between bites of all the other Thanksgiving fare.

